00:04:59.542 --> 00:05:00.750
MASSIMO BOTTURA: Hi everyone.

00:05:02.500 --> 00:05:04.310
I'm Massimo Bottura.

00:05:04.310 --> 00:05:05.750
I'm an Italian chef.

00:05:05.750 --> 00:05:09.363
And I grew up in
Modena-- Modena,

00:05:09.363 --> 00:05:14.430
in the middle of Emilia-Romagna,
in the center of Italy.

00:05:14.430 --> 00:05:20.240
So it is where the Ferrari
car, the Maserati, Lamborghini,

00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:23.622
Ducati, are made, but
also Parmigiano-Reggiano,

00:05:23.622 --> 00:05:24.330
balsamic vinegar.

00:05:25.460 --> 00:05:28.600
So it's like is
the land of-- as I

00:05:28.600 --> 00:05:32.050
said-- slow food and fast car.

00:05:34.320 --> 00:05:41.060
I grew up in a very large family
in which my older brothers,

00:05:41.060 --> 00:05:45.180
they were chasing me all the
time, because I was the younger

00:05:45.180 --> 00:05:45.990
one.

00:05:45.990 --> 00:05:50.780
And my safety place
was the kitchen,

00:05:50.780 --> 00:05:52.830
where my grandmother
was rolling pasta.

00:05:54.026 --> 00:05:58.040
And I could sneak
under the table,

00:05:58.040 --> 00:06:01.220
and she was defending
me with the mattarello,

00:06:01.220 --> 00:06:03.125
rolling the pasta,
saying, get out of here.

00:06:05.360 --> 00:06:08.140
Just because he's the
younger one-- get out!

00:06:09.200 --> 00:06:13.280
So in the meantime, I was
stealing the tortellini

00:06:13.280 --> 00:06:14.840
from up.

00:06:14.840 --> 00:06:18.310
And for me, that's
why tortellini

00:06:18.310 --> 00:06:26.090
are the most important and the
most iconic dish of my life,

00:06:26.090 --> 00:06:28.310
and especially when
they are rolled.

00:06:28.310 --> 00:06:31.590
Because you can feel exactly
the flavor of the filling.

00:06:36.810 --> 00:06:40.279
My father was planning
for me to be a lawyer.

00:06:40.279 --> 00:06:40.945
Can you imagine?

00:06:42.130 --> 00:06:48.840
And so after two
years of my studies,

00:06:48.840 --> 00:06:53.420
I dropped everything--
because my passion

00:06:53.420 --> 00:06:56.640
were food, art, and music.

00:06:57.680 --> 00:07:01.080
And out of the
blue, we found out

00:07:01.080 --> 00:07:05.450
that there was a small
trattoria outside of Modena

00:07:05.450 --> 00:07:06.700
called Trattoria del Campazzo.

00:07:09.330 --> 00:07:11.230
I didn't even know
where it was--

00:07:11.230 --> 00:07:13.460
a small village
with three houses

00:07:13.460 --> 00:07:15.790
and a small restaurant
in the middle.

00:07:17.740 --> 00:07:19.450
My brother took
me there and said,

00:07:19.450 --> 00:07:21.245
this is the perfect
place for you.

00:07:22.490 --> 00:07:25.670
It's the place where
you can express yourself

00:07:25.670 --> 00:07:28.190
through the food,
through your passion.

00:07:28.190 --> 00:07:32.935
Said to Paolo, what do you
think is-- are you sure?

00:07:32.935 --> 00:07:34.390
He said, yes.

00:07:34.390 --> 00:07:35.540
This is the perfect place.

00:07:35.540 --> 00:07:41.050
One week later, I was there,
because the food world

00:07:41.050 --> 00:07:42.050
chose me.

00:07:42.050 --> 00:07:44.510
It's not that I chose that.

00:07:44.510 --> 00:07:45.960
That was the perfect timing.

00:07:46.970 --> 00:07:52.500
And in that moment,
I realized I had

00:07:52.500 --> 00:07:55.570
to put all myself
into this world,

00:07:55.570 --> 00:08:01.530
because I have to show
everyone it was so right,

00:08:01.530 --> 00:08:02.530
the choice I made.

00:08:03.610 --> 00:08:11.267
And the simplest interest
for food, step by step,

00:08:11.267 --> 00:08:11.975
became a passion.

00:08:13.130 --> 00:08:15.020
And through the
passion, I realized

00:08:15.020 --> 00:08:16.105
you can transfer emotions.

00:08:17.210 --> 00:08:22.800
That what I think food is, and
how I interpret the food-- just

00:08:22.800 --> 00:08:24.090
transfer emotions.

00:08:28.090 --> 00:08:32.830
I cooked in Trattoria del
Campazzo for seven years.

00:08:32.830 --> 00:08:37.510
Since once a great chef
from France, Alain Ducasse,

00:08:37.510 --> 00:08:39.770
came and met me.

00:08:39.770 --> 00:08:45.890
He invited me to work at Hotel
de Paris, in Monte Carlo.

00:08:45.890 --> 00:08:46.890
So I went there.

00:08:46.890 --> 00:08:47.970
I left everything.

00:08:47.970 --> 00:08:53.280
I went there and I started
learning, working like 16 hours

00:08:53.280 --> 00:08:55.760
a day-- so to learn
everything, from chocolate

00:08:55.760 --> 00:08:58.880
to bread, baking, everything.

00:08:58.880 --> 00:09:04.310
And since they called
me, Trattoria de Campazzo

00:09:04.310 --> 00:09:08.584
and the [? club-- ?]
Massimo, we need you.

00:09:08.584 --> 00:09:09.500
You have to come back.

00:09:09.500 --> 00:09:10.430
So I left.

00:09:10.430 --> 00:09:12.860
I have to go back
to my real life.

00:09:12.860 --> 00:09:14.360
That was a dream, a bubble.

00:09:15.660 --> 00:09:20.850
And in the moment I was
living in Monte Carlo,

00:09:20.850 --> 00:09:24.000
I met Mr. Ducasse in
the hall of the hotel.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:29.220
And he was asking me, you
know, so, Massimo, did you do?

00:09:29.220 --> 00:09:30.830
Did you have a good experience?

00:09:30.830 --> 00:09:32.640
You know, the classic question.

00:09:32.640 --> 00:09:33.780
I said, fantastic.

00:09:33.780 --> 00:09:34.560
Look at this.

00:09:34.560 --> 00:09:39.560
I have the whole notebook full
of everything, also recipes

00:09:39.560 --> 00:09:41.550
that I've stolen from there.

00:09:41.550 --> 00:09:46.640
So he looked at
me very carefully.

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:52.250
He grabbed the notebook,
and he crash in the middle,

00:09:52.250 --> 00:09:55.180
and he throw in the
garbage, saying,

00:09:55.180 --> 00:09:58.360
you are ready to stand
up with your feet.

00:09:58.360 --> 00:10:00.850
Just walk.

00:10:00.850 --> 00:10:02.030
I was like, in shock.

00:10:02.030 --> 00:10:07.370
I was like, all these months,
all these hours-- you know,

00:10:07.370 --> 00:10:11.960
the sweating and the experience,
everything in the garbage.

00:10:13.150 --> 00:10:14.970
But that was the most
important experience

00:10:14.970 --> 00:10:18.550
of my life, the moment
that changed my life.

00:10:18.550 --> 00:10:22.030
Because in that moment,
in that exact moment,

00:10:22.030 --> 00:10:27.440
I felt I had to do and
I had to express myself

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:30.530
through what I've learned
in all of these months.

00:10:31.730 --> 00:10:33.945
One year later, we opened
Osteria Francescana.

00:10:37.390 --> 00:10:39.830
But everything changed
because of the experience

00:10:39.830 --> 00:10:41.150
in New York and Monte Carlo.

00:10:41.150 --> 00:10:47.030
So those recipes-- they were
so successful in Campazzo,

00:10:47.030 --> 00:10:49.570
in the middle of
the country, they

00:10:49.570 --> 00:10:52.680
couldn't match with
Osteria Francescana,

00:10:52.680 --> 00:10:55.070
because my mind was
already changed.

00:10:55.070 --> 00:10:59.180
And I started thinking about
tradition, but in evolution.

00:10:59.180 --> 00:11:02.160
I was looking at the
terroir in a different way.

00:11:02.160 --> 00:11:06.230
A big wheel of Parmigiano
was no more a cheese to eat,

00:11:06.230 --> 00:11:08.320
but was something
much more deep.

00:11:08.320 --> 00:11:11.400
A drop of balsamic
vinegar was something

00:11:11.400 --> 00:11:15.920
that I had to respect and
see in a different way,

00:11:15.920 --> 00:11:17.710
maybe from under the table.

00:11:17.710 --> 00:11:18.830
I don't know.

00:11:18.830 --> 00:11:27.500
And like that, I started with
my wife this dialogue with art.

00:11:27.500 --> 00:11:35.040
And art-- usually the eye is
the expression of a human being.

00:11:35.040 --> 00:11:38.020
And it makes visible
the invisible.

00:11:38.020 --> 00:11:42.800
So starting from there,
compressing all of these ideas,

00:11:42.800 --> 00:11:45.780
we started creating
edible bites where

00:11:45.780 --> 00:11:49.035
culture became our
motivational force.

00:11:50.400 --> 00:11:56.750
So a few years later,
I had the opportunity

00:11:56.750 --> 00:12:01.120
to meet Ferran Adria, this
Spanish chef who was creating,

00:12:01.120 --> 00:12:04.910
in his restaurant, elBulli,
a revolution on technique.

00:12:04.910 --> 00:12:07.470
And he invited me there, too.

00:12:08.800 --> 00:12:11.220
And so I left
everything another time,

00:12:11.220 --> 00:12:13.390
and I went to elBulli to learn.

00:12:13.390 --> 00:12:17.550
And I was thinking to learn
all of these techniques

00:12:17.550 --> 00:12:22.500
that they could
make me maybe create

00:12:22.500 --> 00:12:23.870
a foam of Parmigiano-Reggiano.

00:12:25.100 --> 00:12:26.020
I don't know.

00:12:26.020 --> 00:12:30.060
And but actually what
Ferran was teaching

00:12:30.060 --> 00:12:34.810
me was freedom-- freedom
to express yourself,

00:12:34.810 --> 00:12:39.410
the freedom of thinking
and looking inside you,

00:12:39.410 --> 00:12:45.710
and bring out all
these memories, ideas,

00:12:45.710 --> 00:12:49.790
through technique but
creative gestures.

00:12:51.520 --> 00:12:54.170
I came back from the
experience at elBulli

00:12:54.170 --> 00:12:58.000
and all these gastronomic
critics in Italy--

00:12:58.000 --> 00:12:59.210
can you imagine?

00:12:59.210 --> 00:13:06.190
In Italy, you don't have to
touch three things-- the Pope,

00:13:06.190 --> 00:13:11.260
the national soccer team,
and the grandmother recipes.

00:13:11.260 --> 00:13:12.570
You can do whatever you want.

00:13:12.570 --> 00:13:16.880
You can do whatever you want,
but not these three things.

00:13:16.880 --> 00:13:18.374
So I was like, oh my god.

00:13:18.374 --> 00:13:19.290
What am I going to do?

00:13:19.290 --> 00:13:20.500
What am I going to do?

00:13:20.500 --> 00:13:22.902
But these gastronomic
critics and the chefs,

00:13:22.902 --> 00:13:25.110
they were playing jokes--
oh, what is he going to do?

00:13:25.110 --> 00:13:27.290
Bottura, he's going to
make like mortadella foam.

00:13:28.820 --> 00:13:30.640
That's a great idea.

00:13:30.640 --> 00:13:31.860
That's a beautiful idea.

00:13:31.860 --> 00:13:33.940
So I'm going to make
a mortadella foam.

00:13:33.940 --> 00:13:35.030
Why?

00:13:35.030 --> 00:13:37.630
In honor of my
mother-- that she was

00:13:37.630 --> 00:13:40.730
the one who pushed me
to be and to follow

00:13:40.730 --> 00:13:42.990
my passion through the kitchen.

00:13:42.990 --> 00:13:50.140
And since I was 14, she was
bringing a bologna sandwich--

00:13:50.140 --> 00:13:52.570
are you calling mortadella
bologna right here?

00:13:52.570 --> 00:13:56.990
So bologna sandwich-- that's
bologna, from Bologna--

00:13:56.990 --> 00:14:00.464
in a backpack, saying,
Massimo, [ITALIAN].

00:14:00.464 --> 00:14:01.130
You have to eat.

00:14:01.130 --> 00:14:03.840
You have to eat if
you want to grow.

00:14:03.840 --> 00:14:05.390
Not just playing soccer.

00:14:05.390 --> 00:14:12.340
And for that
reason, I just start

00:14:12.340 --> 00:14:17.320
thinking about those kinds of
things that are icons for us.

00:14:17.320 --> 00:14:21.440
But trying not to see
and to look at them

00:14:21.440 --> 00:14:25.780
in a nostalgic way,
but in a critic way--

00:14:25.780 --> 00:14:28.160
to bring the best from
the past into the future.

00:14:29.230 --> 00:14:33.990
So one recipe from
another, I started

00:14:33.990 --> 00:14:40.020
getting so
irreverent, so ironic.

00:14:40.020 --> 00:14:43.370
So I was creating
all these plates that

00:14:43.370 --> 00:14:46.370
would provocate people,
provocate the mind.

00:14:46.370 --> 00:14:49.400
But just to attract
the point of view,

00:14:49.400 --> 00:14:52.070
like Tortellini are
Walking on the Broth.

00:14:53.130 --> 00:14:54.590
Serving six tortellini.

00:14:54.590 --> 00:14:57.260
Can you imagine in Modena
serving six tortellini

00:14:57.260 --> 00:14:58.750
in the middle of the broth?

00:14:58.750 --> 00:15:01.922
They were like, what the
hell is he going to do?

00:15:01.922 --> 00:15:02.880
Or what they think is--

00:15:04.020 --> 00:15:06.890
Or Compression of
Pasta and Beans.

00:15:06.890 --> 00:15:08.840
In Compression of
Pasta and Beans,

00:15:08.840 --> 00:15:13.320
I was just thinking about
creating my gastronomic life,

00:15:13.320 --> 00:15:17.830
compress my gastronomic
life into a small glass,

00:15:17.830 --> 00:15:20.554
serving pasta and beans-- one
of the most classic recipes

00:15:20.554 --> 00:15:21.470
of Italian gastronomy.

00:15:22.990 --> 00:15:25.220
But in Compression
of Pasta and Beans,

00:15:25.220 --> 00:15:30.120
I create this sortification
process in a small glass.

00:15:30.120 --> 00:15:34.100
Where at the bottom, there
was like my experience

00:15:34.100 --> 00:15:35.710
with French cuisine.

00:15:35.710 --> 00:15:40.730
So and I was creating
this creme royale.

00:15:40.730 --> 00:15:41.820
Do you know the French?

00:15:41.820 --> 00:15:42.349
No?

00:15:42.349 --> 00:15:42.890
Creme royale.

00:15:44.190 --> 00:15:46.387
So they were adding a
little bit of foie gras.

00:15:46.387 --> 00:15:47.595
It's like "Pulp Fiction", no?

00:15:49.060 --> 00:15:50.259
Royale with cheese.

00:15:50.259 --> 00:15:51.300
It's just a cheeseburger.

00:15:51.300 --> 00:15:52.660
OK?

00:15:52.660 --> 00:15:55.970
So pig skin, beans,
and foie gras.

00:15:55.970 --> 00:15:59.280
And I created this creme
royale on the bottom.

00:15:59.280 --> 00:16:03.890
Then some brunoise
of red radicchio,

00:16:03.890 --> 00:16:05.460
so a little bit of bitterness.

00:16:05.460 --> 00:16:07.715
Saute it with red
wine-- so acidity.

00:16:08.780 --> 00:16:15.690
Then a creamy sauce of beans,
as a very traditional style.

00:16:15.690 --> 00:16:23.430
And then ending with a foam
of very air of rosemary.

00:16:23.430 --> 00:16:27.170
Because rosemary is very
intense and very aggressive.

00:16:27.170 --> 00:16:29.820
So creating an air
of rosemary, you

00:16:29.820 --> 00:16:33.410
have just a little
touch in the back part

00:16:33.410 --> 00:16:36.410
of the palate of the
flavor of rosemary.

00:16:36.410 --> 00:16:40.170
So the first homage
was for Ducasse,

00:16:40.170 --> 00:16:44.230
and the last one was
for Ferran Adria--

00:16:44.230 --> 00:16:46.210
my first and my last
gastronomic experience.

00:16:46.210 --> 00:16:49.440
But in the middle,
instead of serving pasta,

00:16:49.440 --> 00:16:54.290
I introduce Parmigiano-Reggiano
crust boiled into the beans.

00:16:54.290 --> 00:16:57.110
As my grandmother would
say-- because that's

00:16:57.110 --> 00:17:00.470
a secret that every
grandmother knows.

00:17:02.160 --> 00:17:05.920
But I sliced across the
Parmigiano as they were pasta.

00:17:05.920 --> 00:17:10.950
So this kind of
[ITALIAN] like bad cuts.

00:17:10.950 --> 00:17:15.990
So between Ducasse and Ferran
Adria, I put my grandmother.

00:17:15.990 --> 00:17:18.849
That's the idea of
the pasta and beans.

00:17:20.280 --> 00:17:27.000
And after all these years
and all this experience,

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:30.760
we realized that
we were creating

00:17:30.760 --> 00:17:32.390
a very interesting cuisine.

00:17:32.390 --> 00:17:35.270
Because everyone was looking
at us, and especially

00:17:35.270 --> 00:17:36.450
the Michelin Guide.

00:17:38.230 --> 00:17:42.770
And we arrived, at
one point, in which

00:17:42.770 --> 00:17:45.060
we started getting all
these awards and things.

00:17:45.060 --> 00:17:51.050
But people, they
keep giving us space

00:17:51.050 --> 00:17:56.700
in which we had like
this point, this critic

00:17:56.700 --> 00:18:05.520
point of our creativity.

00:18:05.520 --> 00:18:11.290
And at that point,
the dialogue with art

00:18:11.290 --> 00:18:13.650
started getting
more deep and deep.

00:18:13.650 --> 00:18:16.560
And we started
creating plates as they

00:18:16.560 --> 00:18:23.030
were like, more emotional
than just traditional,

00:18:23.030 --> 00:18:26.710
as we are explaining
in the book.

00:18:26.710 --> 00:18:32.720
So we create plates that-- they
start dialogues with yourself,

00:18:32.720 --> 00:18:37.800
with my mind, with the
approach with the people.

00:18:37.800 --> 00:18:40.020
Like, Oops, I Dropped
the Lemon Tart.

00:18:40.020 --> 00:18:41.520
Oops, I Dropped the Lemon Tart.

00:18:41.520 --> 00:18:44.170
Or 1,000 Layers of Leaves.

00:18:44.170 --> 00:18:50.760
It means in a word like this,
full of obsession, obsession

00:18:50.760 --> 00:18:56.620
and obligation, in which
you have, every day,

00:18:56.620 --> 00:18:57.460
I have to go here.

00:18:57.460 --> 00:18:58.310
I have to go there.

00:18:59.390 --> 00:19:02.570
I have to-- the lawyer and
the account and the bank.

00:19:02.570 --> 00:19:04.390
I have to pay the bills.

00:19:04.390 --> 00:19:10.020
You know, if you don't leave a
little space open for poetry,

00:19:10.020 --> 00:19:12.650
this life is going to
disappear like this.

00:19:12.650 --> 00:19:17.690
And if you see
that moment and you

00:19:17.690 --> 00:19:21.280
realize that those moments are
the moments, the most important

00:19:21.280 --> 00:19:26.760
moments in which you can jump
and feel the poetry inside you,

00:19:26.760 --> 00:19:31.025
it's the moment in which you
are in the middle of a service.

00:19:32.200 --> 00:19:34.605
You have your
pastry chef that is

00:19:34.605 --> 00:19:37.220
ready to serve two lemon tart.

00:19:37.220 --> 00:19:40.640
And these are Japanese
guys-- the most precise guys

00:19:40.640 --> 00:19:43.640
in the world, and the
most incredible talented.

00:19:44.770 --> 00:19:47.030
And he drops one of
the two lemon tarts.

00:19:48.230 --> 00:19:50.980
And he's like, ready
to kill himself.

00:19:50.980 --> 00:19:53.250
And he's like, what the hell?

00:19:53.250 --> 00:19:54.270
What's going on?

00:19:54.270 --> 00:19:58.330
I said Taka, it's the most
beautiful tart you can serve.

00:19:58.330 --> 00:19:59.880
It's the imperfection.

00:19:59.880 --> 00:20:02.930
Because you're so perfect
that you create something

00:20:02.930 --> 00:20:05.510
imperfect that I love it.

00:20:05.510 --> 00:20:10.530
And that's the moment in
which we jump into the poetry,

00:20:10.530 --> 00:20:12.720
and we imagine and
we see the world

00:20:12.720 --> 00:20:15.590
from another point of
view, from under the table.

00:20:15.590 --> 00:20:19.200
And in that moment, we create
Oops, I Dropped the Lemon Tart.

00:20:19.200 --> 00:20:22.140
It became an icon of the
international cuisine.

00:20:22.140 --> 00:20:27.090
So what is the book?

00:20:27.090 --> 00:20:34.720
The book is the compression
of 20 years of our work,

00:20:34.720 --> 00:20:40.450
the compression of our passion--
the art, the music, the food.

00:20:40.450 --> 00:20:42.985
It's storytelling.

00:20:44.370 --> 00:20:48.600
Every recipe is a story. it's
more a book about creativity.

00:20:48.600 --> 00:20:50.520
It's more a book about memory.

00:20:52.760 --> 00:20:58.200
What is Italy in
a very deep way?

00:20:58.200 --> 00:21:06.040
Look at foggy parts of Bologna
or the wind of Pantelleria

00:21:06.040 --> 00:21:10.340
that is like giving this
feeling of salty capers

00:21:10.340 --> 00:21:12.590
naturally in the
middle of the sea.

00:21:12.590 --> 00:21:18.370
The magic flavor of an almond
of Noto, or like anchovies

00:21:18.370 --> 00:21:21.040
water from the Gulf of Sorrento.

00:21:21.040 --> 00:21:22.290
So it's about that.

00:21:22.290 --> 00:21:24.140
It's about emotion.

00:21:24.140 --> 00:21:30.190
And it's about the whole life
that I dedicate with my wife,

00:21:30.190 --> 00:21:34.490
with my team-- that I never
forget about the team--

00:21:34.490 --> 00:21:39.830
to create and to give to
everyone, to the young chef,

00:21:39.830 --> 00:21:43.145
the opportunity to imagine
and to dream about the future.

00:21:43.987 --> 00:21:44.820
Thank you very much.

00:21:52.040 --> 00:21:54.140
You're going to
taste-- we brought

00:21:54.140 --> 00:21:57.070
some balsamic vinegar
and some Parmigiano.

00:21:57.070 --> 00:22:02.370
So it's like my
blood in the vein

00:22:02.370 --> 00:22:07.010
and the cheese that made
my muscles like that.

00:22:07.010 --> 00:22:08.640
So I'm not that skinny, right?

00:22:11.070 --> 00:22:15.050
And so just to say,
this vinegar-- and I'm

00:22:15.050 --> 00:22:19.355
very proud of-- just won the
gold medal in Spilamberto

00:22:19.355 --> 00:22:20.730
as the best vinegar
in the world.

00:22:20.730 --> 00:22:23.620
So it's very important
for us that everyone

00:22:23.620 --> 00:22:27.670
thinks that we are so avant
garde, but it's not true.

00:22:29.450 --> 00:22:31.650
We have the feet very
deep into tradition,

00:22:31.650 --> 00:22:33.620
and we really care about that.

00:22:33.620 --> 00:22:35.960
And this is the
expression of what

00:22:35.960 --> 00:22:39.110
we are through Parmigianos,
balsamic vinegar.

00:22:39.110 --> 00:22:43.070
To think about we grew
up as kids listening

00:22:43.070 --> 00:22:46.340
to the sound of the pipes of
the Ferrari or the Maserati.

00:22:47.380 --> 00:22:58.260
But at the end, in a dark
part of the house, where

00:22:58.260 --> 00:23:03.360
the winter hits very heavy or
the summer is getting boiling,

00:23:03.360 --> 00:23:05.660
[INAUDIBLE], there
is balsamic vinegar

00:23:05.660 --> 00:23:10.640
that stayed there for
decades and became,

00:23:10.640 --> 00:23:14.150
after years and years
and years, a liquid gold.

00:23:14.150 --> 00:23:16.600
This is crazy, no?

00:23:16.600 --> 00:23:21.060
For 2014, thinking about that
you create a product that

00:23:21.060 --> 00:23:23.380
takes, like, 25 years
before it tastes?

00:23:25.330 --> 00:23:29.820
But I just brought to share with
you with this kind of emotion.

00:23:33.509 --> 00:23:35.300
FEMALE SPEAKER: Thank
you so much, Massimo.

