00:25:33.610 --> 00:25:34.110
No.

00:25:34.110 --> 00:25:34.651
I don't know.

00:25:34.651 --> 00:25:38.510
Something-- maybe a culatello,
like a slice of culatello,

00:25:38.510 --> 00:25:39.830
very old.

00:25:39.830 --> 00:25:45.150
You chew the same feeling,
like a porcini mushroom,

00:25:45.150 --> 00:25:46.350
black truffle.

00:25:46.350 --> 00:25:48.820
AUDIENCE: What would
you eat for street food

00:25:48.820 --> 00:25:49.920
if you were traveling?

00:25:49.920 --> 00:25:52.880
MASSIMO BOTTURA: Street
food is I love street food.

00:25:52.880 --> 00:25:55.910
Actually, in two days, I'm
going to cook street food too.

00:25:57.340 --> 00:25:59.830
I'm going in New
York, and I create

00:25:59.830 --> 00:26:04.020
a burger for Shake
Shack for Columbus Day.

00:26:05.440 --> 00:26:08.500
And it's going to be
a burger in which I

00:26:08.500 --> 00:26:13.280
mix some beef with cotechino.

00:26:13.280 --> 00:26:15.070
Are you familiar with cotechino?

00:26:15.070 --> 00:26:17.800
Cotechino is a sausage,
very traditional,

00:26:17.800 --> 00:26:21.820
created 500 years ago in
Mirandola, a small village

00:26:21.820 --> 00:26:23.240
outside of Modena.

00:26:23.240 --> 00:26:28.100
And it's just pig ground
with also the skin

00:26:28.100 --> 00:26:31.580
part, that you cook
and you defat it.

00:26:33.080 --> 00:26:38.130
But it's very gelatinous,
and it's incredible

00:26:38.130 --> 00:26:40.480
when there is no
fat, because you

00:26:40.480 --> 00:26:41.900
feel the gelatin everywhere.

00:26:41.900 --> 00:26:44.480
And so I ground this meat.

00:26:44.480 --> 00:26:50.100
I cook it and I mix it with
the gelatin with the beef,

00:26:50.100 --> 00:26:52.680
and some sum
Parmigiano-Reggiano.

00:26:52.680 --> 00:26:57.600
So like 30% to 20% of
cotechino, 70% of meat,

00:26:57.600 --> 00:26:59.540
and 10% of Parmigiano-Reggiano.

00:26:59.540 --> 00:27:02.760
So it's the perfect umami
with the gelatin inside.

00:27:02.760 --> 00:27:06.510
And salsa verde,
as Emilia-Romagna,

00:27:06.510 --> 00:27:09.640
we serve close to the
meat with acidity,

00:27:09.640 --> 00:27:14.160
the chlorophyll of the salad, so
imagine these kinds of things.

00:27:14.160 --> 00:27:18.620
And the mayonnaise made with
balsamic vinegar for the fries.

00:27:19.787 --> 00:27:20.412
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:27:20.412 --> 00:27:22.120
That's Michelin Star
quality street food.

00:27:24.125 --> 00:27:25.250
MASSIMO BOTTURA: I hope so.

00:27:25.250 --> 00:27:26.570
I hope so.

00:27:26.570 --> 00:27:30.010
The point is that
everyone is tweeting that.

00:27:30.010 --> 00:27:34.730
And every single website is
like talking, ah, Columbus Day--

00:27:34.730 --> 00:27:35.900
everyone at Madison Park.

00:27:35.900 --> 00:27:38.210
So can you imagine what's
going on in Madison Park?

00:27:39.990 --> 00:27:43.310
Just last night I was sleeping,
and I wake up like that.

00:27:43.310 --> 00:27:46.070
I see 3,000 people there
waiting for the burger.

00:27:47.380 --> 00:27:48.516
What I'm supposed to do?

00:27:48.516 --> 00:27:49.432
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:27:51.740 --> 00:27:55.080
AUDIENCE: I just wanted
to talk about criticism.

00:27:55.080 --> 00:27:58.710
And I know Italians are very
outspoken in their criticism.

00:27:58.710 --> 00:27:59.419
And you kind of--

00:27:59.419 --> 00:28:00.418
MASSIMO BOTTURA: Really?

00:28:00.418 --> 00:28:01.230
I didn't know that.

00:28:01.230 --> 00:28:02.040
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:28:02.040 --> 00:28:02.540
It's new.

00:28:02.540 --> 00:28:03.900
It's new.

00:28:03.900 --> 00:28:07.080
But you sort of went
away from tradition.

00:28:07.080 --> 00:28:10.550
You almost shocked a culture.

00:28:10.550 --> 00:28:12.856
How do you deal with the
criticism on a daily basis,

00:28:12.856 --> 00:28:14.730
in the restaurant,
outside of the restaurant?

00:28:14.839 --> 00:28:16.380
MASSIMO BOTTURA:
You know, yesterday,

00:28:16.380 --> 00:28:22.990
in the most important
guide, l'Espresso guide,

00:28:22.990 --> 00:28:25.480
from Italy-- it's like
37 years of history.

00:28:25.480 --> 00:28:29.410
He came out for the
fifth time, sixth time,

00:28:29.410 --> 00:28:32.370
like, best chef, best
restaurant in Italy.

00:28:32.370 --> 00:28:35.860
And instead of
saying, ah, great!

00:28:35.860 --> 00:28:39.090
It's beautiful What
a restaurant we have.

00:28:39.090 --> 00:28:40.140
Is like, oh.

00:28:40.140 --> 00:28:41.080
What boring.

00:28:41.080 --> 00:28:42.960
It's always [INAUDIBLE].

00:28:42.960 --> 00:28:46.760
It's like, you know--
what I'm supposed to say?

00:28:46.760 --> 00:28:49.470
Say thank you, or
what do I have to do?

00:28:49.470 --> 00:28:54.150
And it's like, still,
now, after everything,

00:28:54.150 --> 00:28:57.974
there are people that are coming
in with the five different age

00:28:57.974 --> 00:29:00.015
of Parmigiano-Reggiano
and five different texture

00:29:00.015 --> 00:29:00.681
and temperature.

00:29:00.681 --> 00:29:03.530
You know, an iconic
dish that you see

00:29:03.530 --> 00:29:06.790
and that have the
recipe in the book.

00:29:06.790 --> 00:29:10.860
And in the beginning, it
was creating 20 years ago.

00:29:10.860 --> 00:29:17.380
And after it evolved in '98,
the aging process, and 2002,

00:29:17.380 --> 00:29:22.000
and 2011, it has been
declared the plate

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:24.170
of the decade for
Italian gastronomy.

00:29:24.170 --> 00:29:26.190
So it's like an
incredible honor.

00:29:27.605 --> 00:29:31.414
Like two weeks ago, there was
a customer that was like, yeah,

00:29:31.414 --> 00:29:35.160
it's good, but, you know, I
would put something like that,

00:29:35.160 --> 00:29:36.820
and I would change this.

00:29:36.820 --> 00:29:38.830
And I say, oh,
that's a good idea.

00:29:38.830 --> 00:29:43.010
I'm going to take notes, and
I'm going to think about that.

00:29:43.010 --> 00:29:44.330
What do you have to say?

00:29:45.370 --> 00:29:46.510
It's normal.

00:29:46.510 --> 00:29:49.070
In Italy, for me,
I'm used to it.

00:29:49.070 --> 00:29:51.370
So there's no problem.

00:29:51.370 --> 00:29:54.370
15 years ago, I risk
to get the burned

00:29:54.370 --> 00:29:57.050
in the main piazza as a witch.

00:29:58.760 --> 00:29:59.690
So.

00:29:59.690 --> 00:30:01.231
FEMALE SPEAKER: We
can take two more.

00:30:01.627 --> 00:30:02.210
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:30:02.210 --> 00:30:05.530
I had a question on how
you made your vinegar so

00:30:05.530 --> 00:30:09.170
fruitful and sour, on
that perfect blend?

00:30:09.170 --> 00:30:12.220
MASSIMO BOTTURA:
It's just a question.

00:30:12.220 --> 00:30:16.130
It's just a way of waiting.

00:30:17.640 --> 00:30:19.492
Choose the right barrels.

00:30:19.492 --> 00:30:20.450
Choose the right woods.

00:30:22.470 --> 00:30:26.190
Make the perfect musto--
the must, the reduction

00:30:26.190 --> 00:30:30.250
of the grape juice.

00:30:31.450 --> 00:30:33.660
And then wait.

00:30:33.660 --> 00:30:35.940
And then trust your palate.

00:30:35.940 --> 00:30:39.695
Every single wood is
giving you something.

00:30:40.760 --> 00:30:42.270
It's talking to you.

00:30:42.270 --> 00:30:46.200
Like you have juniper,
and it's telling you

00:30:46.200 --> 00:30:51.210
that you're going to have
incense, chocolate, coffee.

00:30:51.210 --> 00:30:52.960
You have cherry wood.

00:30:52.960 --> 00:30:56.960
You're going to have sour
cherry, fresh red fruit,

00:30:56.960 --> 00:30:58.600
a little bit of plants.

00:30:58.600 --> 00:30:59.480
You have oak.

00:31:01.280 --> 00:31:03.570
It's telling you something.

00:31:03.570 --> 00:31:09.490
So what I did-- I just followed
my ideas and my palate.

00:31:09.490 --> 00:31:11.690
I moved different barrels.

00:31:11.690 --> 00:31:15.670
And instead of having
the juniper as everyone

00:31:15.670 --> 00:31:19.100
has at the end of
all these barrels,

00:31:19.100 --> 00:31:23.730
I move the juniper in the middle
and the cherry at the end.

00:31:23.730 --> 00:31:30.360
So I got this fresh and balanced
flavor that is just, to me,

00:31:30.360 --> 00:31:31.960
is just perfect like that.

00:31:31.960 --> 00:31:35.330
And, you know, I got the gold
medal, so they [INAUDIBLE].

00:31:37.610 --> 00:31:40.989
It was a blind tasting, so
no one can say anything.

